{%- comment -%}
  Password field with a show/hide toggle — appears in login, register,
  reset-password, and activate-account, so it's one snippet rather than
  four copies of the same markup. Reuses field.liquid's exact CSS classes
  (field__label/field__control/field__input) rather than a new visual
  pattern; only hand-rolled instead of calling field.liquid directly because
  field.liquid has no slot for a trailing button inside .field__control.

  Works with zero JS: the input is a real type="password" field; the toggle
  button only appears functional once assets/customer-forms.js defines its
  click handler, and CSS keeps it visually present but inert without JS
  (::after cursor stays default) rather than misleadingly interactive.

  Accepts: id (required), name (required), label (required), required (bool),
  autocomplete: passed straight through (e.g. 'current-password', 'new-password').
{%- endcomment -%}
<div class="field">
  <label class="field__label" for="{{ id }}">
    {{ label }}{% if required %} <span aria-hidden="true">*</span>{% endif %}
  </label>
  <div class="field__control password-field__control">
    <input
      class="field__input"
      type="password"
      id="{{ id }}"
      name="{{ name }}"
      {% if autocomplete %}autocomplete="{{ autocomplete }}"{% endif %}
      {% if required %}required aria-required="true"{% endif %}
    >
    <button type="button" class="password-field__toggle" data-password-toggle aria-pressed="false" aria-label="{{ 'customer.show_password' | t }}">
      {% render 'icon', name: 'eye', size: 18, class: 'password-field__icon-show' %}
      {% render 'icon', name: 'eye-off', size: 18, class: 'password-field__icon-hide' %}
    </button>
  </div>
</div>
